There were 1.3 million people living in the Memphis MSA in 2020,
according to the 5-Year American Community Survey. Most of the
population lived within Shelby County (70%), and just under half lived
inside the City of Memphis (48%). While the county and metro area saw
modest increases in population from 2010 to 2020, Memphis had a slight
decrease, enough to consider the population stagnant.
However, the number of households increased in all jurisdictions. How
can the population of the city decrease while the number of households
increase? The answer is a decrease in household size, meaning fewer
people are living together. This is shown by the 3.5% decrease in
average household size over the past decade.
This means that even though the population in the city
remained stagnant, there was still an increase in the demand for
housing over the past decade.
To better see the rate of growth outside of the city, the table below
subtracts Memphis data from Shelby County, and Shelby County data from
the Memphis Metro region.


