While Memphis has a high vacancy rate of 14.6%, the rate is
considerably lower in the county outside the city, at 5.2%. The metro
falls somewhere in the middle at 9.1% vacancy for all housing units.
Removing the county’s data reveals that the outlying metro area saw
an increase in the number of vacant units. Overall, there was an
increase of 12,992 occupied units AND an increase in 1,696 vacant units.
This combination of increased occupancy and vacancy signifies
substantial new development in areas outside Shelby County–at least
14,688 units.
The county saw an increase of 6,903 occupied units and a decrease in
761 vacant units, meaning at least 6,142 new units were developed.
In total, at least 24,411 new housing units were developed in the
Memphis area from 2010-2020, with development primarily in the metro
area outside Shelby County.
Despite most development occurring outside the city limits, Memphis’
high vacancy rate means there is still a large amount of existing
housing that should be available. However, the quality and safety of
these homes may make them uninhabitable, or the costs may be too high
for existing residents to afford. This information is outside the scope
of this post and further research is needed to draw any conclusions.
Conclusion
Memphis’s population stagnated over the past decade, hovering around
635,000 people. Over this same time period, the number of households
increased, driven by a decrease in average household size. This means
that while the population in the city remained stagnant, there was still
an increase in the demand for housing over the past decade.
Areas outside the city saw population/household growth of over 7%.
Despite a recent desire by city officials to increase density, new
development over the past decade was primarily in the metro region
outside the county limits. Memphis’s high vacancy rate should mean there
is still a large amount of the existing housing stock available for
occupancy. Further research is needed on the quality and cost of this
housing to determine actual availability.
